Introduction Huanglongbing (HLB), also known as citrus greening disease, has been found in citrus-growing regions around the world since 1919, devastating citrus crops by reducing fruit quality and yield and eventually causing tree death 1 , 2 , 3 – 4 . In the United States, HLB poses a significant threat to citrus production in California having decimated the citrus industry in Florida 5 , 6 , 7 , 8 – 9 . HLB has resulted in billions of dollars in economic loss since its detection in Florida in 2005 10 , 11 , 12 , 13 – 14 . The Gram-negative Alphaproteobacterium “ Candidatus Liberibacter asiaticus” ( C Las) is the presumed causative agent of HLB in the United States and Asia. This fastidious bacterium replicates exclusively in the phloem cells of citrus and in the insect vector, the Asian citrus psyllid Diaphorina citri Kuwayama (Hemiptera: Psyllidae). In D. citri , C Las is detected both extracellularly and intracellularly in different tissues throughout the psyllid’s lifecycle 6 , 15 . The ability to culture C Las in vitro would advance our knowledge of its biology, facilitate the development of control tools, and allow for validation of the hypothesis that C Las causes HLB through the testing of Koch’s postulates. Numerous attempts to grow C Las in the absence of other bacteria have been unsuccessful 16 , 17 , 18 , 19 – 20 . On the basis that the bacterium replicates within the insect vector, establishment of continuous D. citri cell lines may allow for in vitro C Las replication. In addition to C Las, the microbiome of D. citri includes viruses and endosymbiotic bacteria including Wolbachia and two other bacteria (i.e. Carsonella and Profftella ) that are only found in a specialized organ called the bacteriome 21 , 22 , 23 – 24 . Wolbachia , which infects 50–60% of arthropod species, is widely found in both field-collected and lab-reared D. citri populations 25 , 26 , 27 – 28 . Wolbachia appears to have antiviral impacts in some species 29 , which have been exploited for the management of dengue virus transmission 30 , 31 . Reduced Wolbachia levels are reported to correlate with decreased fitness and increased C Las acquisition in D. citri adults and nymphs 28 , suggesting that Wolbachia could be used to reduce C Las loads in D. citri . Six viruses that infect D. citri have been identified: D. citri reovirus (DcRV), D. citri - associated C virus (DcACV), D. citri flavi-like virus (DcFLV), D. citri densovirus (DcDNV), D. citri picorna-like virus (DcPLV), and D. citri cimodo-like virus (DcCLV) 21 , 24 , 32 , 33 , 34 , 35 , 36 – 37 . All six viruses were present in field-collected D. citri in Florida, with DcACV in 60% of the samples being the most prevalent 21 , 32 , 38 . The relationships between Wolbachia and D. citri -associated viruses and between Wolbachia and C Las, in addition to the fundamental biology of these microbes, remain poorly understood due to the lack of a tractable cell culture system. For this study, we produced three continuous D. citri cell lines from previously generated primary cultures 39 . Characterization of these cell lines through transcriptomics, Sanger sequencing, and immunohistochemistry highlighted differences between the lines in cell type, Wolbachia and virus infection status. These cell lines provide an excellent foundation for analysis of the impact of Wolbachia on D. citri viruses, and potentially also on C Las replication. Methods Subculture of D. citri cell lines and antibiotic treatment D. citri embryo-derived cell cultures were maintained at 28 °C in sealed T25 flasks (Fisher Scientific, FB012936) containing 5 mL of CLG#2 medium each. The CLG#2 medium consisted of EX-CELL 420 (Sigma-Aldrich, 14420C) + L-15 (Sigma-Aldrich, L1518) media at a 1:1 ratio, 9% heat-inactivated fetal bovine serum (Sigma-Aldrich, F4135), and penicillin and streptomycin (Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, US; 15–070-063) at 100 U/mL and 100 µg/mL, respectively 39 . Cells were passaged when the growth of a primary culture entered a stationary phase despite weekly medium replacement, or when the monolayer confluency of a subculture was ≥ 80% for Dici1 (derived from primary culture 2021-9-27#1) and Dici3 (derived from primary culture 2022-2-14#1) 39 , or 70% for Dici5 (derived from primary culture 2022-3-16#1). The Dici5 cell line was established in a manner similar to that used for Dici1 and Dici3 39 . To dissociate attached cells from the flask, the old medium was removed, and cells were briefly rinsed in 1X PBS (Fisher Scientific, 20012027) before trypsinization with 0.05% trypsin–EDTA (Fisher Scientific, 25–300-054) for 2–3 min at 22 °C. After cells became loosely attached, trypsin was removed by aspiration before 2 mL of fresh medium was added to the flask to stop the trypsinization. Cells were suspended in the fresh medium and half of the cell suspension (1 mL), containing approximately 3–4 × 10 6 live cells, was transferred into a new T25 flask containing 4 mL of CLG#2 medium. Approximately 4 duplicate subcultures for each cell line were maintained at any given time, with subcultures passaged on a staggered schedule. This approach ensured continuation of the cell line in case some subcultures were lost. Doxycycline stock solution (5 mg/mL), made by dissolving doxycycline hyclate powder (MilliporeSigma, D9891) in ultrapure water, was filter sterilized using a 0.2 µm syringe filter (Fisher Scientific, NC0789382) and stored in aliquots at −20 °C before use. Doxycycline was applied to Dici1 and Dici5 cells at final concentrations of 0.25 or 0.5 µg/mL, as previously described for elimination of Wolbachia from a mosquito cell line 40 . Doxycycline treatment continued for 14 days during which doxycycline was fully replenished every 3–4 days or on subculturing. Growth analysis Dici3 cells at passage 44 (P44) were dissociated as described above and the cell suspension was used to inoculate 24 T25 flasks at a density of 1.15 × 10 6 cells/flask. Flasks were incubated at 28 °C. Cells from three flasks were harvested through trypsinization as described above before being stained with 0.4% trypan blue (Fisher Scientific, 15–250-061) every 48 h and the live cells were counted using a Countess™ 3 automatic cell counter (ThermoFisher Scientific, AMQAX2000). Confirmation of cell line identity, detection of virus and Wolbachia sequences Genomic DNA was extracted from approximately 4 × 10 6 cells for Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5 cell lines, and 50 D. citri embryos using a Monarch genomic DNA purification kit (New England Biolabs, T3010S). DNA was eluted in 100 µl of elution buffer and quantified using a NanoDrop™ One spectrophotometer (ThermoFisher Scientific, ND-ONE-W). Each 20 µl PCR reaction contained 1X DreamTaq Green PCR Mix (ThermoFisher Scientific, K1081), 0.25 µM of forward and reverse primers (Table 1 ), 50 ng of genomic DNA, and water. The following thermocycler profile was used: 95 °C for 3 min; 35 cycles of 95 °C for 30 s, 60 °C ( cox1 and β-actin )/52 °C ( Wolbachia ftsz )/54 °C ( Wolbachia wsp ) for 30 s, 72 °C for 90 s; and 72 °C for 5 min. Table 1 List of primers used in the current study. Target species Target gene Primer sequence (5’−3’) Amplicon length (bp) References Diaphorina citri cox1 F: GTAGTTGCCCACTTTCACTATGTGC R: CGTCGTGGCATTCCTATAAGTCCT 200 68 Diaphorina citri β-actin F: CCCTGGACTTTGAACAGGAA R: CTCGTGGATACCGCAAGATT 169 27 Wolbachia ftsz F: GTTGTCGCAAATACCGATGC R: CTTAAGTAAGCTGGTATATC 1043 69 Wolbachia wsp F: GGGTCCAATAAGTGATGAAGAAAC R: TTAAAACGCTACTCCAGCTTCTGC 570 70 DcACV RNA1 F: GCCGCACGAAACTAGTGATAAACGCA R: GGATCGGTGGTGCACGAGTATGTAAGTA 473 21 DcRV p8 F: TTTTCCCAGGTACATCGA R: ACCATTCAGCCAGTCCTA 900 21 DcFLV RdRp F: AGGCGAGTACTCCCATCGGATACATT R: GAGGGCCGCTAAGTCTGTAGGACATATT 1400 21 DcCLV RdRp F: ATTTAGGGCCATGTGCAAAG R: CCAACACACCGAGCATACAC 526 21 DcACV: Diaphorina citri-associated C virus ; DcRV: Diaphorina citri reovirus ; DcFLV: Diaphorina citri flavi-like virus ; DcCLV: Diaphorina citri cimodo-like virus ; F: forward primer; R: reverse primer. bp: base pair. To test the presence of D. citri viruses, total RNA was extracted from approximately 4 × 10 6 cells homogenized in 200 µl of TRI Reagent (ThermoFisher Scientific, AM9738) as per the manufacturer’s protocol. RNA pellets were dried and dissolved in 50 µl of water and quantified using a NanoDrop™ One spectrophotometer. cDNA was synthesized using 0.5 mg of RNA with SuperScript III reverse transcriptase (ThermoFisher Scientific, 18080093) and 50 ng of random hexamers. The PCRs were performed in a 20 µl reaction containing 1 µl of diluted cDNA (1:10, v/v), 0.25 µM of forward and reverse primers, 1X DreamTaq Green PCR Mix (ThermoFisher Scientific, K1081), and water. Partial fragments of the DcACV RNA1 gene (473 bp) and DcRV p8 gene (900 bp) were amplified using virus-specific forward and reverse primers (Table 1 ), as described previously 21 . The following thermocycler profile was used: 95 °C for 3 min; 35 cycles of 95 °C for 30 s, 55 °C for 30 s, 72 °C for 60 s; and 72 °C for 5 min. The cox1 , Wolbachia ftsz and wsp , DcACV RNA1, and DcRV p8 PCR products were gel-purified using the Wizard SV Gel and PCR Clean-Up System (Promega, Madison, WI, USA) and sequenced by Azenta/GENEWIZ (Burlington, MA, USA). RNA-seq and transcriptome analysis Cell pellets of Dici1 (P18) and Dici3 (P24) containing approximately 4 × 10 6 cells each were shipped to Azenta/GENEWIZ for RNA extraction, transcriptomic sequencing, and de novo transcriptome assembly. After RNA extraction, rRNA was removed using a QIAseq FastSelect-rRNA Fly Kit (Qiagen, Germantown, MD, USA). cDNA was sequenced using the Illumina HiSeq 4000 platform (2 × 150 bp). FastQC and Trimmomatic were used to assess read data and trim adapter sequences and low-quality reads, respectively 41 , 42 . A separate de novo assembly was generated for each sample using Trinity v2.5.1 43 , followed by quality assessment using TransRate v1.0.3 44 . The remainder of the analyses were performed on the supercomputer HiPerGator at the University of Florida. A combined de novo assembly was also generated from Dici1 and Dici3 reads using Trinity 43 . Assembly completeness was evaluated using BUSCO v4 45 : transcripts from individual sample assemblies and the combined assembly were aligned to the Benchmarking Universal Single-Copy Orthologs (BUSCOs) of the Hemiptera lineage. To investigate the microbial sequence composition of transcriptomes, contiguous sequences (contigs, generated from overlapping reads) from the Dici1 and Dici3 assemblies were mapped to the Diaphorina citri genome (Diaci_v3.0, with endosymbiont sequences removed) from citrusgreening.org 46 using Minimap2 and a divergence allowance of 20% 47 . Similarly, non-host reads were obtained by mapping reads to the D. citri genome using BWA-MEM 48 , 49 . Reads and contigs that did not map to the D. citri genome (non- D. citri, or host-filtered contigs/reads) were extracted from the alignment file with SAMtools 50 . Non- D. citri contigs were used for microbial sequence composition analysis by MMSeqs2 (v14) 51 . Taxonomy assignment against the NCBI nonredundant database 52 was performed using the default algorithm for computing the lowest common ancestor and a minimum open reading frame length of 75 amino acids. Taxonomy results were summarized using the Krona module in MMseqs2 53 . Microbial sequences of interest were verified for further analysis. Dici1 and Dici3 transcriptomes were analyzed for the presence of transcripts of D. citri -associated bacteria that include “ Candidatus Carsonella ruddii” (Gammaproteobacteria: Oceanospirillales), “ Candidatus Profftella armatura” (Betaproteobacteria: Betaproteobacteria incertae sedis), and Wolbachia (Alphaproteobacteria: Rickettsiales) 22 , 23 . Wolbachia (number of orthologs: 364) and Burkholderiales (number of orthologs: 688) lineages are available in BUSCO v4, therefore BUSCO scores were calculated using the non-host contigs from Dici1 or Dici3 as a measure of sequence completeness for these bacteria. For analysis of DcRV sequences, non-host reads were mapped to the D. citri reovirus genome (GenBank: GCA_031538165.1) 33 . Read coverage and read depth were calculated using SAMtools. To quantify the abundance of transcripts in each sample, reads from Dici1 and Dici3 were separately mapped to the combined transcriptome using Salmon (v1.10.1) 54 . The abundance quantification files (containing raw counts) from Salmon were imported into RStudio (v4.3.0) for analysis of differentially expressed transcripts (DETs) using NOISeq 55 . Five technical replicates were simulated during NOISeq analysis, and 20% of the total reads were used to simulate each replicate. Additionally, upper quartile normalization and length correction were performed. The DETs with a probability threshold greater than 0.9 (q = 0.9) were extracted. NOISeq generated transcript expression levels in counts per million (CPM) were used for fold enrichment analysis. Gene ontology (GO) analysis of Dici1 and Dici3 transcripts was performed using eggNOG-mapper (v2.1.6) 56 . Fold enrichment analysis was performed on metabolic, developmental, reproductive, and immune system biological process (BP) GO terms on the transcripts of each cell line. No cross-comparisons were made. Fold enrichment analysis was calculated as follows: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
