				\begin{document}$${\text{log}}_{2}(fold \, enrichment)= {\text{log}}_{2}\left(\frac{Unique \, transcripts \, for \, a \, particular \, GO \, term*100}{Total \, unique \, transcripts}\right)$$\end{document} Fold enrichment analysis was performed on transcripts ≥ 10 CPM. For analysis of tissue-specific marker genes, neuronal and other tissue marker genes were used based on those reported from humans and from insects 57 , 58 , 59 , 60 , 61 – 62 . Wolbachia imaging by use of immunofluorescence confocal microscopy Approximately 1 × 10 6 Dici1 (P43) and Dici3 (P49) cells were seeded per well in 2-well cell culture slides (MatTek, Ashland, MA, USA). The cells were fixed in 4% paraformaldehyde in PBS for 1 h after being incubated at 28 °C for 24 h. Fixed cells were washed three times with PBST (PBS + 0.1% Tween20; ThermoFisher Scientific, J61196.AP + 28320), followed by permeabilization with 0.1% Triton-X 100 (ThermoFisher Scientific, A16046.AE) in PBS for 30 min. Post permeabilization, cells were washed three times with PBST and blocked with blocking buffer (1.5% BSA in PBS) for three hours and then incubated with 3.5 µg/mL of Wolbachia FtsZ specific polyclonal antibody (ThermoFisher Scientific, PA5-117590) in blocking buffer. After three washes with PBST, the cells were incubated for 2 h with 2 µg/mL of Alexa Fluor 488-labeled goat anti-rabbit secondary antibody (ThermoFisher Scientific, A31627). Cells were washed with PBST three times before being mounted with ProLong Diamond Antifade Mountant containing DAPI (ThermoFisher Scientific, P36971) and viewed using a Zeiss confocal system LSM800 microscope. D. citri virus preparation Approximately 1000 field-collected psyllids (~ 600 adults and 400 nymphs) were mixed with 10 mL of 0.01 M phosphate buffer in a 50 mL conical tube (Fisher Scientific, 14–432-22). The tube was then placed in liquid nitrogen for 5 min to freeze the psyllid sample. After freezing, the sample was homogenized as it thawed at room temperature using a polytron homogenizer (VWR, PT 2500 E). The lysate was centrifuged at 5000× g for 15 min to remove debris. The supernatant (~ 9 mL) was collected before being treated with 4 µL of Benzonase nuclease (Sigma-Aldrich, E1014) for 45 min on ice to degrade psyllid nucleic acids. The resulting lysate was then centrifuged at 43,590× g for 25 min, and the supernatant was collected. To enrich D. citri viruses, the supernatant was mixed with 2.3% (w/v) NaCl and 7% (w/v) PEG8000 (Sigma-Aldrich, 154660) on a stir plate at 4 °C overnight. The sample was then centrifuged at 17,400× g for 15 min, and the pellet was resuspended in 3 mL of chilled SM buffer (100 mM NaCl, 8 mM MgSO4, 50 mM Tris–HCl, pH 7.5). After incubating on ice for 1 h, the sample was passed through an 18-gauge needle five times to further degrade any remaining psyllid nucleic acids. The sample was then centrifuged at 12,000× g for 15 min, and the virus-enriched supernatant collected. The supernatant (~ 3 mL) was filter-sterilized using a 0.2 µm syringe filter (Fisher Scientific, NC0789382), then mixed with an equal volume of 60% glycerol. Virus samples were stored as 400 µL aliquots at −80 °C. DNA/RNA extraction was performed using 50 µL of the virus stock, following the manufacturer’s protocol, as described above. Results Establishment of D. citri cell lines Eleven promising cell lines were generated from 41 D. citri primary cultures. Eight cell lines either were lost due to cell death after several passages or had slow growth rates (data not shown). The remaining three cell lines with robust growth rates were passaged more than 40 times and were designated as continuous cell lines Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5 (Table 2 ). The three lines differ in their ability to reach full confluency and passaging intervals, with Dici3 having the shortest passaging interval of 7 days (Table 2 ). While all Dici3 and Dici5 subcultures were passaged successfully, eleven Dici1 subcultures in 7 passages were lost due to cell death (Table 2 ). Notably, those lost Dici1 subcultures appeared indistinguishable from other subcultures that remained healthy before they crashed. Due to the maintenance of duplicate subcultures that survived, the Dici1 line was maintained for > 40 passages (Table 2 ). As of June 2024, Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5 had reached passages, 48, 57, and 42, respectively. Table 2 Overview of continuous Diaphorina citri cell lines. Dici1 Dici3 Dici5 Date of primary culture initiation Sep. 27th, 2021 Feb. 14th, 2022 Mar. 16th, 2022 Age of primary culture at first passaging (days) 436 345 413 Cell morphology Fibroblast (or neuron)-like Fibroblast (or neuron)-like, epithelial-like Fibroblast (or neuron)-like Prevalent tissue-specific markers in the transcriptome Neuronal, oocyte Neuronal, oocyte N.A Maximum confluency (%) 100 100 70 Number of subcultures (/No. of passages) that were lost a 11/7 0/0 0/0 Average passaging interval (days) a 8.5 7.0 8.7 Passage number as of June 3, 2023 48 57 42 Wolbachia b + − + DcRV c + − + DcACV d − − + N.A.: not available. a Evaluated between passages 6 and 40. b Determined by Wolbachia ftsz and wsp PCR. c Determined by DcRV p8 RT-PCR. d Determined by DcACV RNA1 RT-PCR. All three lines consist of adherent cells that are spherical or elongated in shape. These cells show differences in morphology and organization (Fig. 1 ). The vast majority of elongated cells in Dici1 and Dici5 are spindle-shaped or stellate-shaped cells with fine, elongated processes, resembling neurons or fibroblasts. The spherical cells in Dici1 and Dici5 tend to aggregate and form clusters (Fig. 1 A,B,E,F). By comparison, the elongated cells in the Dici3 line possess more diverse morphology. While some of the Dici3 cells have a neuron (or fibroblast)-like morphology, many cells have more rectangular cell bodies and lack elongated processes, suggestive of a different origin (e.g. epithelial). Furthermore, the spherical cells in Dici3 do not tend to form clusters (Fig. 1 C,D). A growth curve was generated for Dici3, the cell line with the shortest passaging interval. The population doubling time was estimated to be approximately 5 days during the exponential growth phase (Supplementary Fig. S1 online). Fig. 1 Photomicrographs of Diaphorina citri cell lines Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5. The morphology and organization of Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5 cells remained relatively consistent between different passages. Clusters of spherical cells in Dici1 and Dici5 are indicated (arrows). The passage number (P) at which each photograph was taken is indicated. Cytochrome-c oxidase subunit 1 ( cox1 ) PCR using genomic DNA from Dici1, Dici3, Dici5 cells, and D. citri embryos all produced products of the expected size (Supplementary Fig. S2). An alignment of cox1 PCR amplicon sequences further confirmed that these cell lines were derived from D. citri (Supplementary Fig. S2). Transcriptomic analysis of Dici1 and Dici3 We further characterized Dici1 and Dici3 cells by sequencing their transcriptomes. RNA extracted from the Dici1 and Dici3 cell lines had high RNA integrity numbers (RIN) (Supplementary Table S1). Additionally, the sequencing depth, exceeding 100 million reads per sample, was comparable for both samples. Individual transcriptomes for Dici1 and Dici3 contained 271,288 and 272,973 contigs, with an N50 of 1444 and 1414 bp, respectively. The assembly generated from the combined reads from both Dici1 and Dici3 contained approximately 400,000 contigs with an N50 of 1515. The percentage of complete BUSCOs evaluated against the hemipteran lineage was highest for the combined assembly (92.3%), compared to 88.1% and 90.0% for the Dici1 and Dici3 assemblies, respectively (Supplementary Table S1). Fold enrichment analysis on metabolic, developmental, reproductive, and immune system Biological Process (BP) Gene Ontology (GO) terms showed that metabolic and developmental were the top 2 BP terms enriched in both cell lines (Supplementary Table S2). A further fold enrichment analysis performed on the BP GO terms associated with the developmental process revealed that nervous system development was the most enriched development process term, which was enriched by 2.86- and threefold in Dici1 and Dici3 transcriptomes, respectively (Supplementary Table S3). Tissue-specific marker gene transcripts Analysis of tissue-specific marker genes showed that most of the neuronal marker gene transcripts (14 out of 16) were detected in Dici1 and Dici3 (Table 3 ). Among the tissue-specific markers, Notch1, a marker for undifferentiated or neurogenic progenitor cells, had the highest transcript levels in Dici1 and Dici3 (Table 3 ). CPM values greater than 10 are considered meaningful for tissue-specific marker transcripts. Most (five out of seven) of the oocyte marker transcripts were also detected in both cell lines, with DDX4 as the most abundant oocyte marker gene (Table 3 ). While seven out of 14 gut marker transcripts were detected, transcripts from only one of seven marker genes were detected for each of hemocytes, and fat body tissue (Table 3 ). Table 3 Abundance of tissue-specific marker gene transcripts in the transcriptomes of Diaphorina citri cell lines Dici1 and Dici3. Dici1 Dici3 No. of transcripts CPM e No. of transcripts CPM e Neuronal markers a elav (ELAVL1,2,3,4) 3 0.04 3 0.08 headcase (HECA) 11 6.09 11 52.61 prospero (PROX1,2) 11 1.23 11 1.19 ciboulot (TMSB4X) 4 0.21 4 0.36 vacht (SLC18A3) ND NA ND NA gad1 (GAD1) ND NA ND NA vglut (SLC17A6,7,8) 14 0.31 14 0.602 vmat (SLC18A1,2) 9 0.80 9 0.752 phm (CYP2U1) 2 0.04 2 0.008 talin1 (TLN1) 41 16.01 37 19.31 Mushasi (MSI1) 12 3.59 12 1.88 Notch1 32 182.97 32 189.2 CDH1 9 0.71 9 0.51 HES1 2 0.03 2 0.042 ARC 22 7.86 22 6.34 bib 11 5.68 11 3.27 Oocyte markers a DDX4 4 17.77 4 8.32 CELF2 13 0.525 13 1.34 YTHDC2 21 2.33 21 1.33 BARD1 4 2.73 4 4.33 GDF9 ND NA ND NA BMP15 ND NA ND NA BRCA2 28 4.22 28 1.63 Gut markers b Trypsin-1 ND NA ND NA Lysozyme M1 ND NA ND NA Aminoacylase-1 10 0.87 10 1.6 Ga