ella or Profftella , which are vertically transmitted on the exterior of the egg, were found in the transcriptomes of the Dici1 and Dici3 cell lines. These bacteria would have been removed during washing of the eggs prior to establishment of the primary cell cultures 39 . The distribution of all bacterial sequences is illustrated in pie charts (visualized using Krona) in Supplementary Fig. S3 and S4 for Dici1 and Dici3, respectively. Table 4 Number of microbial sequences (contigs) annotated within the transcriptomes of Diaphorina citri cell lines Dici1 and Dici3. Dici1 a Dici3 a Bacteria Wolbachia spp. 933 (69.5%) 15 (4.7%) Burkholderiales spp. 29 (13.5%) 19 (0.8%) Total bacterial sequences 1533 b 548 c Fungi Aspergillus niger 0 13 Total fungal sequences 37 d 79 e Viruses Diaphorina citri reovirus 35 14 Total virus sequences 79 f 30 g Total contigs 271,288 272,973 a The percent of complete BUSCOs for the relevant microorganisms are listed in parentheses when applicable. b Figure S3. c Figure S4. d Figure S5. e Figure S6. f Figure S7. g Figure S8. Fungi associated with D. citri include Aspergillus niger , Aureobasidium pullulans , Golubevia pallescens , and Acremonium sclerotigenum 63 . While absent in Dici1, a small number of sequences from Aspergillus niger were present in Dici3 (Table 4 ). The identity of all fungal sequences is shown in Supplementary Fig. S5 and S6. Several transcripts originating from D. citri reovirus (DcRV) (NCBI BioProject accession ID PRJNA293863) were identified by BLASTx analysis. For Dici1, the contigs with 100% query cover had 95% or greater amino acid identity to DcRV transcripts from the NCBI database, although the sequences with lower percentage identities (the lowest being 67.8%) also had low query coverage (< 10%). DcRV transcripts in Dici3, most of which had > 99% query cover had percent amino acid identities ranging between 95 and 100%. As there are only seven DcRV amino acid sequences from BioProject PRJNA293863, Dici1 and Dici3 