anscriptome. Importantly, no Wolbachia -specific gene fragments were amplified from Dici3 genomic DNA and no Wolbachia FtsZ protein was detected in Dici3 cells by immunohistology. Taken together, these data suggest that Wolbachia is absent from Dici3 cells. Furthermore, Dici3 appears to be free of viral infection. Therefore, of the cell lines generated in this study, Dici3, as a virus- and Wolbachia -free cell line, appears to be best suited for the growth and study of D. citri -associated pathogens such as C Las. As expected, many oocyte marker transcripts were found in the two cell lines (i.e. Dici1 and Dici3) for which transcriptome analysis was conducted. Interestingly, unlike marker genes from other tissues such as gut and hemocyte, most neuronal marker gene transcripts were detected in both transcriptomes with many in high abundance. These results indicate that Dici1 and Dici3 may consist of a large number of neuronal progenitors, which is consistent with the fibroblast-like morphology of many cells in these lines. Dici3 is also comprised of cells with non-fibroblast-like morphology, raising the possibility that sublines containing different types of cells may be generated from this line. The presence of multiple markers with low CPM values, combined with expression of markers such as Notch1, headcase and prospero indicates that Dici1 and Dici3 consist predominantly of non-differentiated or early-stage cells. Expression of elav and vacht for example, which are markers of mature neuronal populations was undetected or detected only at low levels (Table 3 ). It is important to note that Notch1, headcase and prospero are not strict markers for specific cell types, but rather dynamic indicators of cellular processes such as proliferation, differentiation and lineage commitment. Although all three cell lines were generated in a similar manner, the composition of sequences from bacteria and viruses are unique for each cell line. Pathogen infections are dynamic within insect populations with only a subset of individuals typically infected at a given time. This situation is reflected by the presence or absence of pathogens in eggs and the resulting cell lines described herein. In contrast to Dici3, Dici1 and Dici5 cells were infected with Wolbachia . While doxycycline treatment negatively impacted insect fitness levels 28 , no overt effect of doxycycline on the morphology or growth of Dici1 or Dici5 cells was observed during two weeks of treatment. Wolbachia could potentially be eliminated from subcultures of the Dici1 and Dici5 cell lines with prolonged doxycycline treatment for assessment of Wolbachia impacts on D. citri cells and on replication of the viruses present in the respective cell lines. Conversely, a subculture of Dici3 could be infected with Wolbachia as a Wolbachia only treatment, although DcRV may also be present in a Dici1 or Dici5-derived inoculum. The D. citri cell lines described here will be an important asset for study of the six D. citri -associated viruses identified to date and for the production of infectious viral clones for potential use in D. citri management 64 . First, Dici1 and Dici5 have the potential to provide for isolation of DcRV and DcACV separate from other viruses that commonly co-infect D. citri 21 . As these two viruses differ in size, they could potentially be isolated from Dici5 cells by differential centrifugation. Second, Dici3 will allow for the study of replication of individual or mixtures of D. citri viruses in the absence of Wolbachia . Third, the impacts of Wolbachia on D. citri virus replication can be assessed as described above. It is notable that of the three cell lines, Dici3, which is virus- and Wolbachia -free is the most robust with the shortest passaging interval and absence of culture crashes (Table 2 ). Based on maintenance of the Dici1 cell line by three independent researchers at the University of Florida, this was the most difficult line to handle with multiple Dici1 subcultures lost during passaging even though all subcultures of Dici1, Dici3, and Dici5 were maintained in the same manner. Whether these Dici1 crashes occurred due to the replication dynamics of Wolbachia and DcRV in combination with cell type and/or additional stressors remains unknown. In contrast, no subcultures of Dici5, which harbors Wolbachia , DcRV and DcACV have been lost. In summary, we have established three continuous D. citri cell lines thereby providing a valuable resource for research on D. citri- associated pathogens. Future research directions include testing of these cell lines for their ability to support the replication of C Las and of D. citri viruses, and the potential for positive or negative interactions between C Las, viruses, and Wolbachia . Whether the neuron-like characteristics of Dici1 and Dici3 impact the ability of non-neuronal pathogens to replicate is a question of particular interest. In addition to their utility for study of D. citri -associated pathogens, these cell lines may also serve as a platform for studying insecticide mechanisms of action, and psyllid physiology including immunology, development, and signal transduction pathways 65 , 66 – 67 .
